{
  "texts": [
    "The methods for automated scoring can be classified into two broad categories: the hand-engineered feature-based approach and the deep learning or LLM-based approach (Haller et al., 2022; Lottridge et al., 2023).",
    "A hybrid of both has proven successful in recent years (Whitmer et al., 2023).Feature-based models primarily utilize handcrafted features ranging from basic elements like word count to more complex aspects such as argumentation structure and coherence.",
    "These features include linguistic features such as syntactic, semantic, lexical, and readability, which are used as input to develop automated scoring models (Ke & Ng, 2019; Uto et al., 2020).",
    "The major modeling approaches (Ramesh & Sanampudi, 2022) include regression-based, classification models, and neural networks.",
    "In the 2021 National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) Automated Scoring Challenge (Whitmer et al., 2023), the hybrid approach integrating handcrafted features and embeddings from BERT (Devlin et al., 2019) or extended BERT models performed slightly better compared with the pure ensemble models from LLMs models (Lottridge et al., 2023; Ormerod, 2022aOrmerod, 2022b))."
  ]
}